						<div style='float:right;margin:0px 0px 15px 15px;font-size:12px;color:#aaa'>2013-07-08 10:09 pm</div>
				                <div>Hi,<br />
The best security measure I've seen so far in terms of protecting against brute force attacks for WP sites is the following plugin:<br />
http://wordpress.org/plugins/all-in-one-wp-security-and-firewall/<br />
It has a &quot;Brute Force Prevention&quot; feature which uses .htacess rules combined with a special cookie. When you enable the feature, the plugin will block all access attempts to your admin area except for those who have the specific cookie in their browser, OR, it allows those who know the special URL which you can set by choosing a secret word in the settings page. <br />
(You will be assigned a special login url by the plugin when you saver the feature's settings).<br />
<br />
Before installing this plugin I noticed that the brute force attacks on my site were reaching epic proportions so-much-so that inmotion had to temporarily make my site unavailable on a number of occassions. <br />
However after installing the above plugin I've had zero brute force issues because they are all being blocked at the .htaccess level.</div>
