						<div style='float:right;margin:0px 0px 15px 15px;font-size:12px;color:#aaa'>2015-01-30 5:36 pm</div>
				                <div>Hi Jacob,<br />
Thanks for the information.<br />
I know this is an old post, but here is what I did as a layer of protection from the brute force.<br />
I added the following line at the beginning of the wp-login.php<br />
if ($_GET['something'] != &quot;value&quot;) { exit(); }<br />
<br />
then edited the line:<br />
&lt;form name=&quot;loginform&quot; id=&quot;loginform&quot; action=&quot;&lt;?php echo esc_url( site_url( 'wp-login.php', 'login_post' ) ); ?&gt;&quot; method=&quot;post&quot;&gt;<br />
<br />
To:<br />
&lt;form name=&quot;loginform&quot; id=&quot;loginform&quot; action=&quot;&lt;?php echo esc_url( site_url( 'wp-login.php?something=value', 'login_post' ) ); ?&gt;&quot; method=&quot;post&quot;&gt;<br />
<br />
And I access the login page as: http://example.com/wp-login.php?something=value<br />
of course anyone can change the &quot;something&quot; and &quot;value&quot; to anything.<br />
<br />
Just a note, the changes might get overridden while updating the WordPress script.<br />
<br />
Best regards,<br />
Ayoob Ali</div>
